30:12.077 --> 30:17.449 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN, PBS NEWSHOUR
CORRESPONDENT: France in the
Caribbean, the islands of
Guadeloupe.

30:17.449 --> 30:24.056 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Pretty much as paradisal as
their P.R. footage portrays
them: French; exotic; with more
than

30:24.056 --> 30:30.195 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a hint of spice. All just four
hours from New York and, if you
book early, for $69 or

30:30.195 --> 30:32.064 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
less, November through April.

30:32.064 --> 30:34.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE:
Flying to Guadeloupe?

30:34.466 --> 30:39.371 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SOLMAN: Because upstart
Norwegian Airlines, some call it
the Southwest Airlines of
Europe,

30:39.371 --> 30:44.710 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is now undercutting the few big
post-merger carriers and their
few foreign partners, which

30:44.710 --> 30:47.913 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
among them control U.S.
skies for travel abroad.

30:47.913 --> 30:51.016 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Anders Lindstrom of Norwegian.

30:51.016 --> 30:54.920 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANDERS LINDSTROM, NORWEGIAN AIR:
So the fare is not unique for a
European airline, it just

30:54.920 --> 31:00.025 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that really highlights how
overpriced the American aviation
market really is.

31:00.025 --> 31:06.965 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: Founded in 1993, the
low-cost airline is profitable,
due to several advantages:

31:06.965 --> 31:12.404 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
high load factors; our plane was
90 percent full; brand-new
Boeings, the most fuel-efficient

31:12.404 --> 31:15.807 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
planes on earth. But
mainly, says Lindstrom --

31:15.807 --> 31:20.479 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LINDSTROM: We don't have all the
decades of maintenance costs and
labor costs that the

31:20.479 --> 31:25.650 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
airlines traditionally do. So,
we're starting with new
aircraft, new crew, which really

31:25.650 --> 31:28.186 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
keeps fares low.

31:28.186 --> 31:32.858 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: And, of course, low
fares tend to mean full planes.
But in the end, says aviation

31:32.858 --> 31:35.594 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
industry watcher
Michael E. Levine --

31:35.594 --> 31:39.197 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL E. LEVINE, NEW YORK
UNIVERSITY: The main difference
is labor arrangements. They're

31:39.197 --> 31:46.104 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a new airline, their pilots have
low seniority, they have more
productive labor arrangements.

31:46.104 --> 31:52.244 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: Arrangements like not
using hubs and instead flying
non-stop point to point so

31:52.244 --> 31:55.947 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
pilots and crew can live near
the airports they fly from. And
that's the Southwest model,

31:55.947 --> 31:57.616 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
right?

31:57.616 --> 32:02.821 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
One type of aircraft, all the
pilots qualified to fly it.

32:02.821 --> 32:06.024 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LINDSTROM: Yes, it's a
simplified version, and that's
something goes across all low
cost

32:06.024 --> 32:08.627 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
airlines around the world.

32:08.627 --> 32:13.265 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: What seemed odd, though,
was that the big carriers, who
used to fly to Guadeloupe

32:13.265 --> 32:19.571 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the '70s, haven't, for years,
save for a few American airlines
flights from Miami.

32:19.571 --> 32:23.508 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How come no American carrier
saw this as an opportunity?

32:23.508 --> 32:27.579 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEROME SIOBUD, GUADELOUPE
AIRPORT: We think that they were
afraid not to fill their plane.

32:27.579 --> 32:32.317 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Norwegian took the risk and they
are now flying full planes.

32:32.317 --> 32:38.190 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: Jerome Siobud manages
Guadeloupe's airport. He says
that because this is legally

32:38.190 --> 32:44.296 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
France, it's part of the
European Union, which in the
1980s voted to prohibit
countries from

32:44.296 --> 32:49.501 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
offering monetary guarantees to
airlines, basically bidding for
their business. So,

32:49.501 --> 32:53.104 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
U.S. carriers abruptly
stopped coming.

32:53.104 --> 32:57.309 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SIOBUD: You know that this is
part of the business and the
industry, as part of the

32:57.309 --> 33:00.478 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
European community, we
can not do that, so --

33:00.478 --> 33:05.917 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: But when Norwegian
decided to test the U.S. market
by flying to now under-served

33:05.917 --> 33:11.056 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Guadeloupe, it demanded no
guarantees. And business boomed.

33:11.056 --> 33:16.528 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SIOBUD: Sixty-thousand thousand
passengers to the U.S. in 2015.
And after three months

33:16.528 --> 33:22.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in 2016, we have 42,000
people flying to the U.S.

33:22.300 --> 33:26.905 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: A more than 150 percent
increase in traffic. The U.S.
seemed ripe for discount

33:26.905 --> 33:30.408 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
global carriers.

33:30.408 --> 33:35.280 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Unfortunately, the U.S.
Department of Transportation was
sitting, for two years, on a
Norwegian

33:35.280 --> 33:39.050 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
request to expand
transatlantic service.

33:39.050 --> 33:41.920 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE: American
pilots don't want Norwegian to
spread its wings.

33:41.920 --> 33:46.491 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SOLMAN: The opposition? Big
carriers and their unions.

33:46.491 --> 33:49.494 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: Only with
your support will we stop this
scheme that threatens the

33:49.494 --> 33:51.897 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
future of U.S. airlines
and their employees.

33:51.897 --> 33:55.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: We are
in a fight for our future.

33:55.533 --> 34:00.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SOLMAN: This video from the
Airline Pilots Association,
titled "The Wolf is at the
Door,"

34:00.005 --> 34:02.707 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
was directed against Norwegian.

34:02.707 --> 34:06.211 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: We must stop
it now or fight the growth of
pilot-shopping around

34:06.211 --> 34:09.114 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the world, at third
world prices.

34:09.114 --> 34:14.352 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LINDSTROM: So they were saying
that we were hiring cheap Asian
labor to operate the flights

34:14.352 --> 34:17.122 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to and from the U.S.,
which is very incorrect.

34:17.122 --> 34:19.557 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
SOLMAN: Again,
Norwegian's Lindstrom.

34:19.557 --> 34:25.196 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LINDSTROM: We have more
U.S.-based cabin crew than any
other international airline. We
have

34:25.196 --> 34:28.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about 300 in the U.S. We will be
tripling if not quadrupling in
the next year as we

34:28.033 --> 34:30.035 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
grow.

34:30.035 --> 34:34.806 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: So in your view, this is
just a classic example of
businesses and labor trying to

34:34.806 --> 34:37.108 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
protect their own turf, or their
own jobs, their own profits?

34:37.108 --> 34:39.611 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LINDSTROM: Yes, very much so.

34:39.611 --> 34:44.215 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
SOLMAN: But with the big
airlines finally making profits
after years of losses, their

34:44.215 --> 34:48.219 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
opposition is understandable,
says industry expert Levine.

34:48.219 --> 34:56.561 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LEVINE: They're not really
interested in seeing anyone else
in. The airlines are afraid that

34:56.561 --> 35:01.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if customers are given the
choice, they'll buy their
tickets somewhere else from
someone

35:01.066 --> 35:05.337 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who will offer them a better
deal. The last I heard, that was
capitalism.

35:05.337 --> 35:10.976 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: On the very day we flew,
as it happens, Norwegian's
request was finally ruled upon.

35:10.976 --> 35:15.580 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We asked Anders Lindstrom about
it after we got to Guadeloupe.

35:15.580 --> 35:18.183 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So yesterday the Department of
Transportation permit you've
been waiting for for two years

35:18.183 --> 35:21.586 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
now finally came through.
This a big deal?

35:21.586 --> 35:25.490 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LINDSTROM: It's a big step. It's
a tentative approval and we're
hoping for the final approval

35:25.490 --> 35:31.262 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in just a few months. That will
mean that we can expand into the
U.S. but also use the

35:31.262 --> 35:35.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
same aircraft, expanding from
Europe into other markets such
as India, South Africa,

35:35.133 --> 35:37.769 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and South America.

35:37.769 --> 35:43.508 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: Meanwhile, what's good
for Norwegian is good for
Guadeloupe. Over-reliant since

35:43.508 --> 35:47.178 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the '80s on just one country for
its second biggest industry,
says tourism official Sandra

35:47.178 --> 35:49.180 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Venite.

35:49.180 --> 35:51.282 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SANDRA VENITE, TOURISM OFFICIAL:
Ninety percent of our tourists
are from mainland France.

35:51.282 --> 35:54.252 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
This is the people
that are here.

35:54.252 --> 35:57.956 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: And so the deal with
Norwegian is low cost, no frills
fares to get the American

35:57.956 --> 36:00.225 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
tourists back?

36:00.225 --> 36:05.597 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VENITE: Yes, exactly. For once,
it benefited us to be French, to
get an airline flying

36:05.597 --> 36:08.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
from the U.S. to the French
Caribbean. How crazy is that?

36:08.933 --> 36:10.035 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

36:10.035 --> 36:14.305 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SOLMAN: But $69 fares from
New York and watch out!

36:14.305 --> 36:18.676 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
VENITE: We have capacity to
absorb the demand. We just need
more Americans in Guadeloupe.

36:18.676 --> 36:22.380 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We need to go back to where
we were in the '70s.

36:22.380 --> 36:28.520 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLMAN: And with real airline
competition, Guadeloupe expects
to get there. As for Norwegian s

36:28.520 --> 36:31.289 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
future, says Michael
E. Levine --

36:31.289 --> 36:38.663 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LEVINE: You can do the kind of
thing we're talking about pretty
well as a new, relatively

36:38.663 --> 36:47.472 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
small niche airline. As you
grow, your labor force becomes
more senior. You're under a

36:47.472 --> 36:54.712 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
lot of the pressures that make
these other airlines less
efficient. Norwegian's challenge

36:54.712 --> 37:00.652 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is to figure out how to grow and
maintain its competitive edge.
That is something that

37:00.652 --> 37:05.690 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
many airlines have failed
at over the years.

37:05.690 --> 37:11.129 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SOLMAN: But it's not something
that Guadeloupe has to worry
about, it seems, not for a
while.

37:11.129 --> 37:17.669 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the PBS "NewsHour" --
come on in, the water's fine!

37:17.669 --> 37:31.049 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is economics correspondent
Paul Solman, reporting from
France, in the Caribbean.

37:31.049 --> 37:36.254 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
