battles around them.

42:45.396 --> 42:51.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Even now, we've chosen not to
present his most controversial
work. But the new exhibition,

42:51.202 --> 42:54.205 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
"Robert Mapplethorpe: The
Perfect Medium", wants us to see
how much more there was to

42:54.205 --> 42:56.140 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the artist.

42:56.140 --> 42:57.341 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRITT SALVESEN, LOS ANGELES
COUNTY MUSEUM OF ART: This
gallery gets us to the 1980s

42:57.341 --> 42:58.810 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
--

42:58.810 --> 43:03.047 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BROWN: Britt Salvesen is a
curator at the Los Angeles
County Museum of Art.

43:03.047 --> 43:10.087 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SALVESEN: For several years
after the culture wars debate of
the late '80s, early '90s,

43:10.087 --> 43:17.528 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it was impossible to see the
work as art because we were
preoccupied with its status as
evidence,

43:17.528 --> 43:19.230 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
let's say.

43:19.230 --> 43:22.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
BROWN: As part of
that culture war.

43:22.200 --> 43:27.772 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SALVESEN: Yes. And that really
forestalled an assessment of his
artwork.

43:27.772 --> 43:33.110 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BROWN: Mapplethorpe grew up in a
conservative Irish Catholic
household in Queens, New York,

43:33.110 --> 43:39.150 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and in the 1970s became part of
the city's burgeoning gay scene.
He focused from the

43:39.150 --> 43:44.755 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
beginning on three main
subjects: portraiture, including
artists and celebrities of the
day,

43:44.755 --> 43:48.459 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
floral still lifes,
and sex and the body.

43:48.459 --> 43:53.164 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SALVESEN: Those are very
traditional art historical
subjects, I mean long before
photography.

43:53.164 --> 43:59.804 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So the question becomes, how do
you make them your own? And I
think Mapplethorpe does it

43:59.804 --> 44:06.310 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
through a refinement, a
reduction of extraneous
elements. His sense of
perfection and beauty

44:06.310 --> 44:09.313 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is what he applies to those
traditional subjects.

44:09.313 --> 44:11.549 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL MARTINEAU, PAUL GETTY
MUSEUM: He has to be in table
position, right in the center

44:11.549 --> 44:13.217 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
--

44:13.217 --> 44:17.855 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BROWN: Paul Martineau curated a
companion exhibition at the
Getty Museum. The two museums

44:17.855 --> 44:22.727 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
acquired the artist's archives
from the Mapplethorpe Foundation
five years ago.

44:22.727 --> 44:28.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARTINEAU: You won't find wilted
flowers in his pictures. He
liked flowers at their most

44:28.866 --> 44:34.972 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
powerful and most erect. Once
they started wilting, he'd get
rid of them. He really didn't

44:34.972 --> 44:37.575 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
like flowers. He liked
pictures of flowers.

44:37.575 --> 44:41.112 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BROWN: Was he after perfection?
Was he after beauty?

44:41.112 --> 44:45.883 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MARTINEAU: He was after
perfection. And beauty was high
up there as well.

44:45.883 --> 44:51.989 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BROWN: One regular subject was
Patti Smith, the poet and later
famed rock musician. She

44:51.989 --> 44:56.694 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
wrote about their youthful times
in her National Book Award
winning memoir, "Just Kids," and

44:56.694 --> 45:02.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in 2010 told me about her friend
and the ambition they shared.

45:02.166 --> 45:06.103 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PATTI SMITH, SINGER/SONGWRITER:
Robert really believed in
himself. Robert was a very
interesting

45:06.103 --> 45:14.145 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
boy, because he was quite shy,
yet absolutely confident in his
abilities and that he would

45:14.145 --> 45:18.015 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
someday, you know, achieve
acclaim. He saw his --

45:18.015 --> 45:19.517 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
BROWN: He knew that,
he felt that?

45:19.517 --> 45:22.820 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
SMITH: He felt that, absolutely.

45:22.820 --> 45:29.160 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BROWN: He would achieve fame,
but for the public at large that
came in 1989 when North

45:29.160 --> 45:33.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Carolina Senator Jesse Helms
took to the Senate floor to
decry federal funding for a
traveling

45:33.731 --> 45:36.100 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
exhibition of
Mapplethorpe's work.

45:36.100 --> 45:40.671 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEN. JESSE HELMS (R), NORTH
CAROLINA: I don't even
acknowledge that it's art. I
don't even

45:40.671 --> 45:43.908 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
acknowledge that the fellow who
did it was an artist. I think he
was a jerk.

45:43.908 --> 45:49.146 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BROWN: Bowing to political
pressure, Washington's Corcoran
Museum cancelled the show, and
when

45:49.146 --> 45:52.683 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it went on to the Cincinnati
Arts Center, its director was
arrested and charged with

45:52.683 --> 45:57.021 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
obscenity. He was
later acquitted.

45:57.021 --> 46:02.727 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But Mapplethorpe's work would
for years after be seen in this
context. The Los Angeles
exhibitions

46:02.727 --> 46:08.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
contain the controversial work,
accompanied by warning signs of
their explicit content.

46:08.699 --> 46:14.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mapplethorpe himself, this is
his last self-portrait, died of
AIDS, at age 42, just before the
cultural

46:14.572 --> 46:16.841 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
tempest burst.

46:16.841 --> 46:20.978 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FENTON BAILEY, FILMMAKER: He
said that his life was the work
of art and the pictures

46:20.978 --> 46:28.019 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
were secondary. The ultimate
work of art as far as he was
concerned was his life.

46:28.019 --> 46:34.191 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BROWN: His life? So, I mean,
he's creating himself as a work
of art? Is that --

46:34.191 --> 46:41.332 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RANDY BARBATO, FILMMAKER: And
documenting his life. I think
that's part of why so much

46:41.332 --> 46:49.540 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of his art has such impact,
because there's an honesty to
it. There's an intimacy to it.

46:49.540 --> 46:51.409 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: Everything
was a means to an end to his
career.

46:51.409 --> 46:54.412 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: He
was a new type of art.

46:54.412 --> 47:00.051 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BROWN: In conjunction with the
joint exhibition, filmmakers
Fenton Bailey and Randy Barbato

47:00.051 --> 47:03.921 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
released an HBO documentary
called "Look at the Pictures," a
portrait of the man and his

47:03.921 --> 47:05.790 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
times.

47:05.790 --> 47:07.158 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: The whole
point of being an artist is to
learn about yourself, the

47:07.158 --> 47:17.134 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
photographs I think are less
important than the life that
one s leading.

47:17.134 --> 47:23.240 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BAILEY: I think he was playing
something of a game of cat and
mouse with his audience

47:23.240 --> 47:28.512 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and critics. I think he knew
that it would provoke, but he
also said he never was intending

47:28.512 --> 47:30.347 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to shock people.

47:30.347 --> 47:34.685 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BROWN: I mean, do you take that
at face value? How could it not
shock people?

47:34.685 --> 47:39.356 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BAILEY: I do and I don't. You
know, exactly. I mean, he knew
that the key here was to
photograph

47:39.356 --> 47:46.931 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
things, to document things that
people considered outside of the
realm of art. The way he did

47:46.931 --> 47:52.136 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it was to elevate them and make
them beautiful. The composition
and the lighting was incredible.

47:52.136 --> 47:58.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, he made what other
people just dismissed as
pornography, he made it art, and
made us

47:58.109 --> 48:00.444 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
look at it seriously.

48:00.444 --> 48:07.184 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BARBATO: It's ironic, we live in
a world now where you can access
the most explicit imagery

48:07.184 --> 48:14.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at the tip of, you know, at your
fingertips, yet as a society
we're still incredibly
puritanical

48:14.625 --> 48:27.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about sex. And so his images
still, the explicit ones, I
think people still find it
challenging

48:27.905 --> 48:32.143 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and uncomfortable. And I think
that's important. I I think it's
important for people to ask

48:32.143 --> 48:35.045 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
themselves why.

48:35.045 --> 48:39.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BROWN: And these many years
later, as "Robert Mapplethorpe:
The Perfect Medium" shows,
there's

48:39.283 --> 48:42.987 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
also much to look at anew.

48:42.987 --> 48:49.560 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
From Los Angeles, I m Jeffrey
Brown for "The PBS NewsHour".

48:49.560 --> 48:54.565 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(END VIDEOTAPE)

48:54.565 --> 49:01.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SREENIVASAN: Finally, another
installment in our brief but
spectacular series. Tonight,

49:01.038 --> 49:05.976 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we hear from 91-year-old Flossie
Lewis. A former English teacher,
she now lives at the

49:05.976 --> 49:10.047 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Piedmont Gardens Senior Living
Community in the Bay Area. Lewis
keeps busy by writing

49:10.047 --> 49:13.117 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
fiction and offers us insight on
what it feels like to grow old.

49:13.117 --> 49:15.019 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(BEGIN VIDEOTAPE)

49:15.019 --> 49:18.856 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FLOSSIE LEWIS, 91-YEAR-OLD:
Getting old is a state of mind.
Now, I m 91. I m badly

49:18.856 --> 49:25.162 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
crippled, but I still think
I m 15. Will this go viral?

49:25.162 --> 49:31.602 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
UNIDENTIFIED MALE: We hope so.

49:31.602 --> 49:41.912 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LEWIS: There are several ways I
keep myself stimulated. By
dragging myself to Piedmont

49:41.912 --> 49:47.985 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Avenue on my walker or in my
wheelchair, and you should see
me use my wheelchair.

49:47.985 --> 49:52.890 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I write light verse for "The
Crest" which is our newspaper,
and every month you can

49:52.890 --> 49:58.329 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
find a sly little bit of
verse from Flossie Lewis.

49:58.329 --> 50:05.236 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The other way I keep being
stimulated is just watching
politics. And if that isn't
enough

50:05.236 --> 50:13.210 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to drive you crazy, I don't know
what is. You do struggle to keep
yourself neat and

50:13.210 --> 50:16.347 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
clean and fashionable.

50:16.347 --> 50:27.391 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And there is always the
possibility that romance comes
your way. Just liking someone is
a treat

50:27.391 --> 50:35.399 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
because part of being old is to
get cranky. There is indigestion
and your teeth fall out

50:35.399 --> 50:43.908 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and suddenly you need hearing
aides and you feel increasingly
unattractive, and then somebody

50:43.908 --> 50:49.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
says, "How nice you look today,
Mrs. Lewis! Or, you're a real
kick, Flossie!"

50:49.513 --> 50:56.153 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And you feel good about
yourself. You pick yourself up
and you say, "I m going to get

50:56.153 --> 51:01.759 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
through it. I m going to get
through it because I have a
reason to get through it."

51:01.759 --> 51:07.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Really growing old is when you
discover that you haven't a
reason to get through it
anymore,

51:07.364 --> 51:16.106 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and that you would like to go to
sleep with a certain amount of
dignity. Accepting the

51:16.106 --> 51:27.618 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
fact the body is going to go but
the personality doesn't have to
go, and that thing which is

51:27.618 --> 51:35.092 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the hardest to admit is that
character doesn't have to go.

51:35.092 --> 51:42.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I m Flossie Lewis. This is my
brief but spectacular take on
growing old.

51:42.933 --> 51:44.768 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(END VIDEOTAPE)

